<p><b>Mercedes-Benz</b> (<small>German pronunciation:</small> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_German" title="Help:IPA for German">[mtsedsbnts]</a></span>) is a global automobile manufacturer and a division of the German company <a href="/wiki/Daimler_AG" title="Daimler AG">Daimler AG</a>. The brand is known for <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">luxury vehicles</a>, buses, <a href="/wiki/Coach_(vehicle)" class="mw-redirect" title="Coach (vehicle)">coaches</a>, and trucks. The headquarters is in <a href="/wiki/Stuttgart" title="Stuttgart">Stuttgart</a>, <a href="/wiki/Baden-W%C3%BCrttemberg" title="Baden-Wrttemberg">Baden-Wrttemberg</a>.</p>
<p>The name first appeared in 1926 under <a href="/wiki/Daimler-Benz" title="Daimler-Benz">Daimler-Benz</a>, but traces its origins to <a href="/wiki/Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft" title="Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft">Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft</a>'s 1901 <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes (car)">Mercedes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Karl_Benz" title="Karl Benz">Karl Benz</a>'s 1886 <a href="/wiki/Benz_Patent-Motorwagen" title="Benz Patent-Motorwagen">Benz Patent-Motorwagen</a>, which is widely regarded as the first gasoline-powered <a href="/wiki/Automobile" class="mw-redirect" title="Automobile">automobile</a>. The slogan for the brand is "the best or nothing" and Mercedes-Benz was one of the top growing brands in 2014 with 18% growth.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup></p>
<p></p>

</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg/170px-Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg" width="170" height="212" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg/255px-Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg/340px-Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2519" data-file-height="3148" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Gottlieb_Daimler_1890s2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Gottlieb_Daimler" title="Gottlieb Daimler">Gottlieb Daimler</a>, founder of <a href="/wiki/Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft" title="Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft">Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Mercedes-Benz traces its origins to <a href="/wiki/Karl_Benz" title="Karl Benz">Karl Benz</a>'s creation of the first <a href="/wiki/Petrol_engine" title="Petrol engine">petrol</a>-powered car, the <a href="/wiki/Benz_Patent_Motorwagen" class="mw-redirect" title="Benz Patent Motorwagen">Benz Patent Motorwagen</a>, financed by <a href="/wiki/Bertha_Benz" title="Bertha Benz">Bertha Benz</a><sup id="cite_ref-EAHF_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EAHF-2">[2]</a></sup> and patented in January 1886,<sup id="cite_ref-MBoverview_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MBoverview-3">[3]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Gottlieb_Daimler" title="Gottlieb Daimler">Gottlieb Daimler</a> and engineer <a href="/wiki/Wilhelm_Maybach" title="Wilhelm Maybach">Wilhelm Maybach</a>'s conversion of a stagecoach by the addition of a petrol engine later that year. The <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes (car)">Mercedes</a> automobile was first marketed in 1901 by Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft. (Daimler Motors Corporation). <a href="/wiki/Emil_Jellinek" title="Emil Jellinek">Emil Jellinek</a>, an Austrian automobile entrepreneur who worked with DMG created the trademark in 1902, naming the 1901 Mercedes 35&#160;hp after his daughter <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_Jellinek" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes Jellinek">Mercedes Jellinek</a>. The first Mercedes-Benz <a href="/wiki/Brand_name" class="mw-redirect" title="Brand name">brand name</a> vehicles were produced in 1926, following the merger of Karl Benz's and Gottlieb Daimler's companies into the Daimler-Benz company.<sup id="cite_ref-MBoverview_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MBoverview-3">[3]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Markenregister_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Markenregister-4">[4]</a></sup> On 28 June 1926, Mercedes Benz was formed with the merger of Karl Benz and Gottlieb Daimler's two companies.</p>
<p>Gottlieb Daimler was born on 17 March 1834 in Schorndorf. After training as a gunsmith and working in France, he attended the Polytechnic School in Stuttgart from 1857 to 1859. After completing various technical activities in France and England, he started work as a draftsman in Geislingen in 1862. At the end of 1863, he was appointed workshop inspector in a machine tool factory in Reutlingen, where he met Wilhelm Maybach in 1865.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2017)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>Throughout the 1930s, Mercedes-Benz produced the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_770" title="Mercedes-Benz 770">770</a> model, a car that was popular during Germany's <a href="/wiki/Nazi_Germany" title="Nazi Germany">Nazi</a> period. <a href="/wiki/Adolf_Hitler" title="Adolf Hitler">Adolf Hitler</a> was known to have driven these cars during his time in power, with <a href="/wiki/Bulletproof" class="mw-redirect" title="Bulletproof">bulletproof</a> windshields.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> Most of the surviving models have been sold at auctions to private buyers. One of them is currently on display at the <a href="/wiki/Canadian_War_Museum" title="Canadian War Museum">War Museum</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ottawa" title="Ottawa">Ottawa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ontario" title="Ontario">Ontario</a>. The pontiff's <a href="/wiki/Popemobile" title="Popemobile">Popemobile</a> has often been sourced from Mercedes-Benz.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> In 1944, 46,000 forced laborers were used in Daimler-Benz's factories to bolster Nazi war efforts. The company later paid $12 million in reparations to the laborers' families.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> Mercedes-Benz has introduced many technological and safety <a href="#Innovations">innovations</a> that later became common in other vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-8">[8]</a></sup> Mercedes-Benz is one of the best-known and established automotive brands in the world.</p>
<p>For information relating to the famous three-pointed star, see under the title <a href="/wiki/Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft" title="Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft">Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft</a> including the merger into Daimler-Benz.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Subsidiaries_and_alliances">Subsidiaries and alliances</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Subsidiaries and alliances">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>As part of the Daimler AG company, the Mercedes-Benz Cars division includes Mercedes-Benz and <a href="/wiki/Smart_(marque)" title="Smart (marque)">Smart</a> car production.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Mercedes-AMG">Mercedes-AMG</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Mercedes-AMG">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG" title="Mercedes-AMG">Mercedes-AMG</a> became a majority owned division of Mercedes-Benz in 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> The company was integrated into DaimlerChrysler in 1999,<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> and became Mercedes-Benz AMG beginning on 1 January 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Mercedes-Maybach">Mercedes-Maybach</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Mercedes-Maybach">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Daimler's ultra-luxury brand <a href="/wiki/Maybach" title="Maybach">Maybach</a> was under Mercedes-Benz cars division until 2013, when the production stopped due to poor sales volumes. It now exists under the Mercedes-Maybach name, with the models being ultra-luxury versions of Mercedes cars, such as the 2016 Mercedes-Maybach S600.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="China">China</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: China">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Daimler coorporates with <a href="/wiki/BYD_Auto" title="BYD Auto">BYD Auto</a> to make and sell a battery-electric car called <a href="/wiki/Denza" title="Denza">Denza</a> in China.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> In 2016, Daimler announced plans to sell Mercedes-Benz branded all-electric battery cars in China.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Production">Production</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Production">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Quality_rankings">Quality rankings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Quality rankings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz,_M%C3%BAnich,_Alemania,_2013-03-30,_DD_21.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG/220px-Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG" width="220" height="140" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG/330px-Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG/440px-Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz%2C_M%C3%BAnich%2C_Alemania%2C_2013-03-30%2C_DD_21.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4761" data-file-height="3034" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Concesionario_de_Mercedes-Benz,_M%C3%BAnich,_Alemania,_2013-03-30,_DD_21.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mercedes-Benz dealer in Munich, Germany.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Since its inception, Mercedes-Benz had maintained a reputation for its quality and durability. Objective measures looking at <a href="/wiki/Passenger_vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="Passenger vehicles">passenger vehicles</a>, such as <a href="/wiki/J._D._Power" class="mw-redirect" title="J. D. Power">J. D. Power</a> surveys, demonstrated a downturn in reputation in these criteria in the late 1990s and early 2000s. By mid-2005, Mercedes temporarily returned to the industry average for initial quality, a measure of problems after the first 90&#160;days of ownership, according to J. D. Power.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> In J. D. Power's Initial Quality Study for the first quarter of 2007, Mercedes showed dramatic improvement by climbing from 25th to 5th place and earning several awards for its models.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> For 2008, Mercedes-Benz's initial quality rating improved by yet another mark, to fourth place.<sup id="cite_ref-2008jdpower_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2008jdpower-32">[32]</a></sup> On top of this accolade, it also received the Platinum Plant Quality Award for its Mercedes Sindelfingen, Germany assembly plant.<sup id="cite_ref-2008jdpower_32-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2008jdpower-32">[32]</a></sup> J. D. Power's 2011 US Initial Quality and Vehicle Dependability Studies both ranked Mercedes-Benz vehicles above average in build quality and reliability.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup> In the 2011 UK J. D. Power Survey, Mercedes cars were rated above average.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> A 2014 <a href="/wiki/ISeeCars.com" title="ISeeCars.com">iSeeCars.com</a> study for Reuters found Mercedes to have the lowest vehicle recall rate.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup></p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Current_model_range">Current model range</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Current model range">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Mercedes-Benz offers a full range of passenger, light commercial and heavy commercial equipment. Vehicles are manufactured in multiple countries worldwide. The <a href="/wiki/Smart_(marque)" title="Smart (marque)">Smart</a> <a href="/wiki/Marque" class="mw-redirect" title="Marque">marque</a> of <a href="/wiki/City_car" title="City car">city cars</a> are also produced by Daimler AG.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_A-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz A-Class">A-Class</a> <a href="/wiki/Hatchback" title="Hatchback">Hatchback</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_B-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz B-Class">B-Class</a> <a href="/wiki/Multi_Purpose_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Multi Purpose Vehicle">Multi Purpose Vehicle</a> (MPV)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_C-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz C-Class">C-Class</a> <a href="/wiki/Saloon_(automobile)" class="mw-redirect" title="Saloon (automobile)">Saloon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Estate_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Estate car">Estate</a>, <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coup">Coup</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cabriolet" class="mw-redirect" title="Cabriolet">Cabriolet</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_CLA-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz CLA-Class">CLA-Class</a> 4 Door Coup and Estate</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_CLS-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class">CLS-Class</a> 4 Door Coup and Estate</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_E-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz E-Class">E-Class</a> Saloon, Estate, Coup and <a href="/wiki/Cabriolet" class="mw-redirect" title="Cabriolet">Cabriolet</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_G-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz G-Class">G-Class</a> <a href="/wiki/Sports_Utility_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Sports Utility Vehicle">Sports Utility Vehicle</a> (SUV)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_GLA-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz GLA-Class">GLA-Class</a> Compact Sports Utility Vehicle (SUV)/ Crossover</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_GLC-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz GLC-Class">GLC-Class</a> Sports Utility Vehicle (SUV)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_GLE-Class" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz GLE-Class">GLE-Class</a> Sports Utility Vehicle (SUV)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_GL-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz GL-Class">GLS-Class</a> Large Sports Utility Vehicle (SUV)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">S-Class</a> Luxury Saloon, Coup &amp; Cabriolet</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_SL-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz SL-Class">SL-Class</a> Grand Tourer</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_SLK-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz SLK-Class">SLC-Class</a> Roadster</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_V-Class" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz V-Class">V-Class</a> Multi Purpose Vehicle (MPV)/ Van</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG_GT" title="Mercedes-AMG GT">AMG GT</a> Sports car/ Supercar</li>
</ul>

<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg/220px-S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg" width="220" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg/330px-S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg/440px-S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="1024" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:S404-300TDI-erg-chebbi.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Unimog" title="Unimog">Unimog</a>, a famous allround vehicle by Mercedes-Benz</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Mercedes-Benz Trucks is now part of the Daimler Trucks division, and includes companies that were part of the DaimlerChrysler merger. Gottlieb Daimler sold the world's first truck in 1886.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> The first factory to be built outside Germany after WWII was in Argentina. It originally built trucks, many of which were modified independently to buses, popularly named <a href="/wiki/Colectivo" title="Colectivo">Colectivo</a>. Today, it builds buses, trucks and the Sprinter van.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2013)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Buses">Buses</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Buses">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_buses" title="Mercedes-Benz buses">Mercedes-Benz buses</a></div>
<p>Mercedes-Benz produces a wide range of buses and coaches, mainly for Europe and Asia. The first model was produced by Karl Benz in 1895.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Significant_models_produced">Significant models produced</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Significant models produced">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>

<p>The <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_600" title="Mercedes-Benz 600">Mercedes-Benz 600</a> or 600S Pullman Guard limousines offer the option of armour-plating and have been used by <a href="/wiki/Official_state_car" title="Official state car">diplomats</a> worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Car_nomenclature">Car nomenclature</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Car nomenclature">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Until 1994, Mercedes-Benz utilized an alphanumeric system for categorizing their vehicles, consisting of a number sequence approximately equal to the engine's displacement in liters multiplied by 100, followed by an arrangement of alphabetical suffixes indicating body style and engine type.</p>
<ul>
<li>"C" indicates a coupe or cabriolet body style (for example, the CL and CLK models, though the C-Class is an exception, since it is also available as a sedan or station wagon).</li>
<li>"D" indicates the vehicle is equipped with a diesel engine.</li>
<li>"E" (for "Einspritzung") indicates the vehicle's engine is equipped with petrol <a href="/wiki/Fuel_injection" title="Fuel injection">fuel injection</a>. In most cases (the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_600" title="Mercedes-Benz 600">600</a> limousine and Mercedes E-Class being the exceptions), if neither "E" or "D" is present, the vehicle has a petrol engine with a carburettor.</li>
<li>"G" was originally used for the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_G-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz G-Class">Gelndewagen</a> off-road vehicle, but is now applied to Mercedes SUVs in general (for example, the GLA and GLK).</li>
<li>"K" was used in the 1930s, indicating a supercharger ("Kompressor") equipped engine. Two exceptions&#160;: the SSK and CLK, where K indicates "Kurz" (short-wheelbase).</li>
<li>"L" indicates "Leicht" (lightweight) for sporting models, and "Lang" (long-wheelbase) for sedan models.</li>
<li>"R" indicates "Rennen" (racing), used for racing cars (for example, the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300SLR" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz 300SLR">300SLR</a>).</li>
<li>"S" Sonderklasse "Special class" for flagship models, including the S-Class, and the SL-Class, SLR McLaren and SLS sportscars.</li>
<li>"T" indicates "Touring" and an estate (or station wagon) body style.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some models in the 1950s also had lower-case letters (b, c, and d) to indicate specific trim levels. For other models, the numeric part of the designation does not match the engine displacement. This was done to show the model's position in the model range independent of displacement or in the price matrix. For these vehicles, the actual displacement in liters is suffixed to the model designation. An exception was the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W201" title="Mercedes-Benz W201">190-class</a> with the numeric designation of "190" as to denote its entry level in the model along with the displacement label on the right side of the boot (190E 2.3 for 2.3-litre 4-cylinder petrol motor, 190D 2.5 for 2.5-litre 5-cylinder diesel motor, and so forth). Some older models (such as the SS and SSK) did not have a number as part of the designation at all.</p>
<p>For the 1994 model year, Mercedes-Benz revised the naming system. Models were divided into "classes" denoted by an arrangement of up to three letters (see "Current model range" above), followed by a three-digit (or two-digit for AMG models, with the number approximately equal to the displacement in litres multiplied by 10) number related to the engine displacement as before. Variants of the same model such as an estate version or a vehicle with a diesel engine are no longer given a separate letter. The SLR, SLS and GT supercars do not carry a numerical designation.</p>
<p>Today, many numerical designations no longer reflect the engine's actual displacement but more of the relative performance and marketing position. Despite its engine displacement in two litres, the powerplant in the A45 AMG produces 355 brake horsepower so the designation is higher as to indicate the greater performance. Another example is the E250 CGI having greater performance than the E200 CGI due to the different engine tuning even though both have 1.8-litre engines. From the marketing perspective, E200 seems more "upscale" than E180. Recent AMG models use the "63" designation (in honor of the 1960s 6.3-litre <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M100_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M100 engine">M100</a> engine) despite being equipped with either a 6.2-litre (<a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M156_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M156 engine">M156</a>), a 5.5-litre (<a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M278_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M278 engine">M157</a>) or even a 4.0-litre engine.</p>
<p>Some models carry further designations indicating special features:</p>
<ul>
<li>"<a href="/wiki/4MATIC" class="mw-redirect" title="4MATIC">4MATIC</a>" indicates the vehicle is equipped with <a href="/wiki/Four-wheel_drive" title="Four-wheel drive">all-wheel-drive</a>.</li>
<li>"<a href="/wiki/BlueTec" title="BlueTec">BlueTEC</a>" indicates a diesel engine with <a href="/wiki/Selective_catalytic_reduction" title="Selective catalytic reduction">selective catalytic reduction</a> exhaust aftertreatment.</li>
<li>"BlueEFFICIENCY" indicates special fuel economy features (direct injection, <a href="/wiki/Start-stop_system" title="Start-stop system">start-stop system</a>, aerodynamic modifications, etc.)</li>
<li>"CGI" (Charged Gasoline Injection) indicates <a href="/wiki/Direct_fuel_injection" class="mw-redirect" title="Direct fuel injection">direct gasoline injection</a>.</li>
<li>"CDI" (Common-rail Direct Injection) indicates a <a href="/wiki/Common_rail" title="Common rail">common-rail</a> diesel engine.</li>
<li>"Hybrid" indicates a petrol- or diesel-electric <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_vehicle" title="Hybrid vehicle">hybrid</a>.</li>
<li>"NGT" indicates a natural gas-fueled engine.</li>
<li>"Kompressor" indicates a <a href="/wiki/Supercharger" title="Supercharger">supercharged</a> engine.</li>
<li>"Turbo" indicates a <a href="/wiki/Turbocharger" title="Turbocharger">turbocharged</a> engine, only used on A-, B-,E- and GLK-Class models.</li>
<li>"AMG Line" indicates the interior or engine, depending which car, has been fitted with the luxuries of their AMG sports cars</li>
</ul>
<p>Model designation badges can be deleted at the request of the customer.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="2015_and_beyond">2015 and beyond</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: 2015 and beyond">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Rationalisation of the model nomenclature was announced in November 2014 for future models.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> The changes consolidate many confusing nomenclature and their placements in the model range such as CL-Class is now called the S-Class Coup. The naming structure is divided into four categories: core, off-road vehicle/SUV, 4-door coup, and roadster. <b>AMG GT</b>, and <b>V-Class</b> are unaffected by the change. In October 2016, Mercedes unveiled the X-Class; a <a href="/wiki/Pickup_truck" title="Pickup truck">pickup truck</a> built on the <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Navara#Mercedes-Benz_X-Class" title="Nissan Navara">Nissan Navara</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> At the <a href="/wiki/2016_Paris_Motor_Show" title="2016 Paris Motor Show">2016 Paris Motor Show</a>, the company announced the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_EQ" title="Mercedes-Benz EQ">EQ</a>, a family of upcoming <a href="/wiki/Battery_electric_vehicle" title="Battery electric vehicle">battery electric vehicles</a> based on a modular <a href="/wiki/Car_platform" title="Car platform">platform</a>, expected to represent up to 25% of its global sales by 2025.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup></p>

<p>The revised A45 AMG for 2016 model year on has shifted the model designation to the right side while AMG is on the left side.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup> This trend commenced with Mercedes-Maybach with MAYBACH on the left and S500/S600 on the right.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Environmental_record">Environmental record</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Environmental record">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Mercedes-Benz has developed multi <a href="/wiki/Concept_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Concept vehicle">concept cars</a> with alternative propulsion, such as hybrid-electric, fully electric, and fuel-cell <a href="/wiki/Powertrain" title="Powertrain">powertrains</a>. At the 2007 <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_motor_show" class="mw-redirect" title="Frankfurt motor show">Frankfurt motor show</a>, Mercedes-Benz showed seven hybrid models, including the F700 <a href="/wiki/Concept_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Concept vehicle">concept car</a>, powered by a hybrid-electric drivetrain featuring the <a href="/wiki/DiesOtto" title="DiesOtto">DiesOtto</a> engine.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup> In 2009, Mercedes-Benz displayed three <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_BlueZERO" title="Mercedes-Benz BlueZERO">BlueZERO</a> concepts at the <a href="/wiki/North_American_International_Auto_Show" title="North American International Auto Show">North American International Auto Show</a>. Each car features a different powertrain - battery-electric, fuel-cell electric, and gasoline-electric hybrid.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> In the same year, Mercedes also showed the Vision S500 PHEV concept with a 19 miles (31&#160;km) <a href="/wiki/All-electric_range" title="All-electric range">all-electric range</a> and <a href="/wiki/Greenhouse_gas" title="Greenhouse gas">CO<sub>2</sub> emissions</a> of 74&#160;grams/km in the <a href="/wiki/New_European_Driving_Cycle" title="New European Driving Cycle">New European Driving Cycle</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2002, Mercedes-Benz has developed the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_F-Cell" title="Mercedes-Benz F-Cell">F-Cell</a> fuel cell vehicle. The current version, based on the B-Class, has a 250-mile range and is available for lease, with volume production scheduled to begin in 2014. Mercedes has also announced the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_SLS_AMG" title="Mercedes-Benz SLS AMG">SLS AMG E-Cell</a>, a fully electric version of the SLS sports car, with deliveries expected in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[51]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S400_BlueHYBRID" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz S400 BlueHYBRID">Mercedes-Benz S400 BlueHYBRID</a><sup id="cite_ref-daimler.com_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-daimler.com-52">[52]</a></sup> was launched in 2009, and is the first production automotive hybrid in the world to use a <a href="/wiki/Lithium-ion_battery" title="Lithium-ion battery">lithium-ion battery</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">[54]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup> In mid-2010, production commenced on the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_Vito" title="Mercedes-Benz Vito">Vito E-Cell</a> all-electric van. Mercedes expects 100 vehicles to be produced by the end of 2010 and a further 2000 by the end of 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2008, Mercedes-Benz announced that it would have a demonstration fleet of small electric cars in two to three years.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> Mercedes-Benz and Smart are preparing for the widespread uptake of electric vehicles (EVs) in the UK by beginning the installation of <a href="/wiki/Recharging_point" class="mw-redirect" title="Recharging point">recharging points</a> across their <a href="/wiki/Car_dealership" title="Car dealership">dealer</a> networks. So far 20 <a href="/wiki/Elektrobay" class="mw-redirect" title="Elektrobay">Elektrobay</a> recharging units, produced in the UK by Brighton-based <a href="/wiki/Elektromotive" title="Elektromotive">Elektromotive</a>, have been installed at seven locations as part of a pilot project, and further expansion of the initiative is planned later in 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the United States, Mercedes-Benz was assessed a record US$30.66&#160;million fine for their decision to not meet the federal <a href="/wiki/Corporate_average_fuel_economy" class="mw-redirect" title="Corporate average fuel economy">corporate average fuel economy</a> standard in 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup> Certain Mercedes-Benz cars, including the S550 and all AMG models sold in the United States, also face an additional <a href="/wiki/Energy_Tax_Act" title="Energy Tax Act">gas guzzler tax</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup> However, newer AMG models fitted with the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M278_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M278 engine">M157</a> engine will not be subject to the gas-guzzler tax, due to improved fuel economy,<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">[61]</a></sup> and newer models powered by the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M276_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M276 engine">M276</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_M278_engine" title="Mercedes-Benz M278 engine">M278</a> engines will have better fuel economy. In 2008, Mercedes also had the worst CO<sub>2</sub> average of all major European manufacturers, ranking 14th out of 14 manufacturers.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">[62]</a></sup> Mercedes was also the worst manufacturer in 2007 and 2006 in terms of average CO<sub>2</sub> levels, with 181&#160;g and 188&#160;g of CO<sub>2</sub> emitted per km, respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[63]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Bicycles">Bicycles</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Bicycles">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Mercedes-Benz Accessories GmbH introduced three new bicycles in 2005,<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup> and the range has developed to include the patent pending Foldingbike in 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">[65]</a></sup> Other models include the Mercedes-Benz Carbon Bike,<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> Trekking Bike,<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">[67]</a></sup> Fitness Bike<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> and the Trailblazer Bike.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Motorsport">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_motorsport" title="Mercedes-Benz in motorsport">Mercedes-Benz in motorsport</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedessimplex1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Mercedessimplex1.jpg/220px-Mercedessimplex1.jpg" width="220" height="177" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Mercedessimplex1.jpg/330px-Mercedessimplex1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Mercedessimplex1.jpg/440px-Mercedessimplex1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="826" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedessimplex1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A DMG <a href="/wiki/Mercedes_Simplex" title="Mercedes Simplex">Mercedes Simplex</a> 1906 in the <a href="/wiki/Deutsches_Museum" title="Deutsches Museum">Deutsches Museum</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The two companies which were merged to form the <i>Mercedes-Benz</i> brand in 1926 had both already enjoyed success in the new sport of <a href="/wiki/Auto_racing" title="Auto racing">motor racing</a> throughout their separate histories. A single Benz competed in the world's first motor race, the <a href="/wiki/Paris%E2%80%93Rouen_(motor_race)" title="ParisRouen (motor race)">1894 ParisRouen</a>, where mile Roger finished 14th in 10 hours 1 minute. Throughout its long history, the company has been involved in a range of motorsport activities, including <a href="/wiki/Sports_car_racing" title="Sports car racing">sports car racing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rally_racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Rally racing">rallying</a>. On several occasions Mercedes-Benz has withdrawn completely from motorsport for a significant period, notably in the late 1930s, and after the <a href="/wiki/1955_Le_Mans_disaster" title="1955 Le Mans disaster">1955 Le Mans disaster</a>, where a <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300_SLR" title="Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR">Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR</a> rammed another car (An Austin-Healey), took off into the stands, and killed more than 80 spectators. <a href="/wiki/Stirling_Moss" title="Stirling Moss">Stirling Moss</a> and co-driver <a href="/wiki/Denis_Jenkinson" title="Denis Jenkinson">Denis Jenkinson</a> made history by winning the 1955 <a href="/wiki/Mille_Miglia" title="Mille Miglia">Mille Miglia</a> road race in Italy during a record-breaking drive with an average speed of almost 98&#160;mph in a <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300_SLR" title="Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR">Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup></p>
<p>Although there was some activity in the intervening years, it was not until 1987 that Mercedes-Benz returned to front line competition, returning to Le Mans, <a href="/wiki/Deutsche_Tourenwagen_Meisterschaft" title="Deutsche Tourenwagen Meisterschaft">Deutsche Tourenwagen Meisterschaft</a> (DTM), and <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> with <a href="/wiki/Sauber" title="Sauber">Sauber</a>. The 1990s saw Mercedes-Benz purchase British engine builder <a href="/wiki/Ilmor" title="Ilmor">Ilmor</a> (now <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_High_Performance_Engines" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz High Performance Engines">Mercedes-Benz High Performance Engines</a>), and campaign <a href="/wiki/IndyCar_Series" title="IndyCar Series">IndyCars</a> under the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Automobile_Club" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Automobile Club">USAC</a>/<a href="/wiki/Champ_Car" title="Champ Car">CART</a> rules, eventually winning the <a href="/wiki/1994_Indianapolis_500" title="1994 Indianapolis 500">1994 Indianapolis 500</a> and <a href="/wiki/1994_CART_World_Series_season" class="mw-redirect" title="1994 CART World Series season">1994 CART IndyCar World Series</a> Championship with <a href="/wiki/Al_Unser,_Jr." class="mw-redirect" title="Al Unser, Jr.">Al Unser, Jr.</a> at the wheel. The 1990s also saw the return of Mercedes-Benz to GT racing, and the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_CLK_GTR" title="Mercedes-Benz CLK GTR">Mercedes-Benz CLK GTR</a>, both of which took the company to new heights by dominating the FIA's GT1 class.</p>
<p>Mercedes-Benz is currently active in four motorsport categories, <a href="/wiki/Formula_Three" title="Formula Three">Formula Three</a>, <a href="/wiki/Deutsche_Tourenwagen_Masters" title="Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters">DTM</a>, <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> and <a href="/wiki/FIA_GT3_European_Championship" title="FIA GT3 European Championship">GT3</a>.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Formula_One">Formula One</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Formula One">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg/220px-Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg" width="220" height="220" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg/330px-Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg/440px-Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedes_duo_2013_Malaysia.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Both <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Mercedes-AMG</a> Formula One cars at the <a href="/wiki/2013_Malaysian_Grand_Prix" title="2013 Malaysian Grand Prix">2013 Malaysian Grand Prix</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Mercedes-Benz in Formula One</a></div>
<p>Mercedes-Benz took part in the world championship in 1954 and 1955, but despite being successful with two championship titles for <a href="/wiki/Juan-Manuel_Fangio" class="mw-redirect" title="Juan-Manuel Fangio">Juan-Manuel Fangio</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup> the company left the sport after just two seasons. Fangio is considered by many to be the best F1 driver in history.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup></p>
<p>Mercedes-Benz returned as an engine supplier in the 1990s and part-owned <a href="/wiki/Team_McLaren" class="mw-redirect" title="Team McLaren">Team McLaren</a> for some years, to which it has supplied engines engineered by <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_HighPerformanceEngines" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines">Ilmor</a><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">[73]</a></sup> since 1995. This partnership brought success, including drivers championships for <a href="/wiki/Mika_H%C3%A4kkinen" title="Mika Hkkinen">Mika Hkkinen</a> in 1998 and 1999, and for <a href="/wiki/Lewis_Hamilton" title="Lewis Hamilton">Lewis Hamilton</a> in 2008, as well as a constructors championship in 1998. The collaboration with McLaren had been extended into the production of roadgoing cars such as the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_SLR_McLaren" title="Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren">Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren</a>.</p>
<p>In 2007, McLaren-Mercedes was fined a record US$100&#160;million for stealing confidential Ferrari technical data.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[74]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2009, <a href="/wiki/Ross_Brawn" title="Ross Brawn">Ross Brawn</a>'s newly conceived Formula One team, <a href="/wiki/Brawn_GP" title="Brawn GP">Brawn GP</a> used Mercedes engines to help win the constructor's championship, and <a href="/wiki/Jenson_Button" title="Jenson Button">Jenson Button</a> to become champion in the F1 drivers' championship. At the end of the season, Mercedes-Benz sold its 40% stake in McLaren to the McLaren Group and bought 70% of the Brawn GP team jointly with an Abu Dhabi-based investment consortium. Brawn GP was renamed <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Mercedes GP</a> for the 2010 season and is, from this season on, a works team for Mercedes-Benz. As of 2017, the company currently provides engines to <a href="/wiki/Williams_Grand_Prix_Engineering" title="Williams Grand Prix Engineering">Williams Martini Racing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Force_India" title="Force India">Sahara Force India F1 Team</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[75]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2014, Mercedes clinched its first F1 Constructor's title with drivers <a href="/wiki/Lewis_Hamilton" title="Lewis Hamilton">Lewis Hamilton</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nico_Rosberg" title="Nico Rosberg">Nico Rosberg</a> with 3 races to go, after dominating much of the season. Mercedes repeated its dominance in 2015 in similar fashion, losing only 3 races out of 19 once again. Mercedes yet again dominated in 2016, losing only 2 races out of 21.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Logo_history">Logo history</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Logo history">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In June 1909, Daimler-Motoren-Gesellschaft (DMG) registered both a three-pointed and a four-pointed star as trademarks, but only the three-pointed star was used. To DMG, the star symbolized Adolf Daimler's aims for universal motorization: on land, water and in the air.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">[76]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Noted_employees">Noted employees</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Noted employees">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Paul_Bracq" title="Paul Bracq">Paul Bracq</a> major designer of automobiles in the 20th century</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/B%C3%A9la_Bar%C3%A9nyi" title="Bla Barnyi">Bla Barnyi</a> car safety pioneer (rigid passenger safety shell), joined Daimler-Benz in 1937<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">[77]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Wilhelm_Maybach" title="Wilhelm Maybach">Wilhelm Maybach</a> automotive pioneer, first met Gottlieb Daimler in 1865<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Ferdinand_Porsche" title="Ferdinand Porsche">Ferdinand Porsche</a> founder of Porsche, joined Mercedes in 1923 and developed the <a href="/wiki/Kompressor_(Mercedes-Benz)" title="Kompressor (Mercedes-Benz)">Kompressor</a> <sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Bruno_Sacco" title="Bruno Sacco">Bruno Sacco</a> joined Daimler-Benz as a designer in 1958. Head of Design in 1975, retired in 1999<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Uhlenhaut" title="Rudolf Uhlenhaut">Rudolf Uhlenhaut</a> joined Daimler-Benz in 1931, his designs included the <a href="/wiki/Silver_Arrows" title="Silver Arrows">Silver Arrows</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300SL" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz 300SL">300 SL</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300_SLR" title="Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR">300SLR</a><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[81]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Adolf_Eichmann" title="Adolf Eichmann">Adolf Eichmann</a> former Nazi criminal. Worked in Argentina's factory after WWII<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Rudolf_Caracciola" title="Rudolf Caracciola">Rudolf Caracciola</a> one of the greatest GP drivers in history drove MB <a href="/wiki/Silver_Arrows" title="Silver Arrows">Silver Arrows</a> in competition.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Josef_Ganz" title="Josef Ganz">Josef Ganz</a> - Technical consultant and "Godfather" of the *<a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W136" title="Mercedes-Benz W136">Mercedes-Benz W136</a>, with the revolutionary Independent suspension, <a href="/wiki/Swing_axle" title="Swing axle">Swing axle</a> layout.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Juan_Manuel_Fangio" title="Juan Manuel Fangio">Juan Manuel Fangio</a> - Five time Formula 1 World Champion, honorary president of Mercedes-Benz Argentina from 1987 until his death in 1995.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Michael_Schumacher" title="Michael Schumacher">Michael Schumacher</a> - Seven time <a href="/wiki/Formula_1" class="mw-redirect" title="Formula 1">Formula 1</a> World Champion, drove for Mercedes in the <a href="/wiki/World_Sportscar_Championship" title="World Sportscar Championship">World Endurance Championship</a> in the 80s and then in their <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_in_Formula_One" title="Mercedes-Benz in Formula One">Formula One Team</a> from <a href="/wiki/2010_Formula_One_Season" class="mw-redirect" title="2010 Formula One Season">2010</a> till <a href="/wiki/2012_Formula_One_season" title="2012 Formula One season">2012</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Innovations">Innovations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Innovations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Numerous technological innovations have been introduced on Mercedes-Benz automobiles throughout the many years of their production, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Internal_combustion_engine" title="Internal combustion engine">internal combustion engine</a> automobile was developed independently by Benz and Daimler &amp; Maybach in 1886</li>
<li>Daimler invented the honeycomb radiator of the type still used on all water-cooled vehicles today</li>
<li>Daimler invented the float <a href="/wiki/Carburetor" title="Carburetor">carburetor</a> which was used until replaced by <a href="/wiki/Fuel_injection" title="Fuel injection">fuel injection</a></li>
<li>The "drop chassis" the car originally designated the "Mercedes" by Daimler was also the first car with a modern configuration, having the carriage lowered and set between the front and rear wheels, with a <a href="/wiki/Front-engine_design" class="mw-redirect" title="Front-engine design">front engine</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rear-wheel_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear-wheel drive">powered rear wheels</a>. All earlier cars were "horseless carriages", which had high centres of gravity and various engine/drive-train configurations</li>
<li>The first passenger road car to have <a href="/wiki/Brake" title="Brake">brakes</a> on all four wheels (1924)<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_83-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-83">[83]</a></sup></li>
<li>In 1936, the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_260_D" title="Mercedes-Benz 260 D">Mercedes-Benz 260 D</a> was the first diesel-powered passenger car.</li>
<li>Mercedes-Benz were the first to offer direct fuel injection on the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_300SL" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz 300SL">Mercedes-Benz 300SL</a> Gullwing</li>
<li>The "safety cage" or "<a href="/wiki/Automobile_safety" title="Automobile safety">safety cell</a>" construction with front and rear <a href="/wiki/Crumple_zones" class="mw-redirect" title="Crumple zones">crumple zones</a> was first developed by Mercedes-Benz in 1951. This is considered by many as the most important innovation in automobile construction from a safety standpoint<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-8">[8]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title="The material near this tag needs to be fact-checked with the cited source(s). (September 2009)">verification needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>In 1959, Mercedes-Benz patented a device that prevents drive wheels from spinning by intervening at the engine, transmission, or brakes. In 1987, Mercedes-Benz applied its patent by introducing a <a href="/wiki/Traction_control_system" title="Traction control system">traction control system</a> that worked under both braking and acceleration</li>
<li>an Anti-Lock Brake system (ABS) was first offered on the W116 450SEL 6.9. They became standard on the W126 S-Class starting production in 1979 and first sold in most markets in 1980.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Airbag" title="Airbag">Airbags</a> were first introduced in the European market, beginning with model year 1981 S-Class.</li>
<li>Mercedes-Benz was the first to introduce pre-tensioners to <a href="/wiki/Seat_belt" title="Seat belt">seat belts</a> on the 1981 S-Class. In the event of a crash, a pre-tensioner will tighten the belt instantaneously, removing any 'slack' in the belt, which prevents the occupant from jerking forward in a crash</li>
<li>In September 2003, Mercedes-Benz introduced the world's first seven-speed <a href="/wiki/Automatic_transmission" title="Automatic transmission">automatic transmission</a> called '<a href="/wiki/7G-Tronic" class="mw-redirect" title="7G-Tronic">7G-Tronic</a>'</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Electronic_stability_control" title="Electronic stability control">Electronic Stability Programme</a> (ESP), <a href="/wiki/Brake_assist" class="mw-redirect" title="Brake assist">brake assist</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">[84]</a></sup> and many other types of safety equipment were all developed, tested, and implemented into passenger cars first by Mercedes-Benz. Mercedes-Benz has not made a large fuss about its innovations, and has even licensed them for use by competitors in the name of improving automobile and passenger safety. As a result, crumple zones and anti-lock brakes (ABS) are now standard on all modern vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-8">[8]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title="The material near this tag needs to be fact-checked with the cited source(s). (September 2009)">verification needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
</ul>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG/220px-Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG" width="220" height="173" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG/330px-Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG/440px-Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1522" data-file-height="1200" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mercedes-Benz_M156_Engine_02.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mercedes M156 engine</div>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W211" class="mw-redirect" title="Mercedes-Benz W211">(W211) E320 CDI</a> which has a <a href="/wiki/Variable_geometry_turbocharger" class="mw-redirect" title="Variable geometry turbocharger">variable geometry turbocharger</a> (VGT) 3.0-litre <a href="/wiki/V6_engine" title="V6 engine">V6</a> <a href="/wiki/Common_rail" title="Common rail">common rail</a> diesel engine (producing 224&#160;hp or 167&#160;kW), set three world <a href="/wiki/Endurance" title="Endurance">endurance</a> records. It covered 100,000 miles (160,000&#160;km) in a record time, with an average speed of 224.823&#160;km/h (139.70&#160;mph). Three identical cars did the endurance run (one set above record) and the other two cars set world records for time taken to cover 100,000 kilometres (62,137&#160;mi) and 50,000 miles (80,000&#160;km) respectively. After all three cars had completed the run, their combined distance was 300,000 miles (480,000&#160;km) (all records were FIA approved).<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title="Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title="The text near this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. (June 2011)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li>
<li>Mercedes-Benz pioneered a system called <a href="/wiki/Pre-Safe" class="mw-redirect" title="Pre-Safe">Pre-Safe</a> to detect an imminent crash and prepares the car's safety systems to respond optimally. It also calculates the optimal braking force required to avoid an accident in emergency situations, and makes it immediately available for when the driver depresses the brake pedal. Occupants are also prepared by tightening the seat belt, closing the sunroof and windows, and moving the seats into the optimal position.</li>
<li>At 181 horsepower per litre, the M133 engine installed in Mercedes-Benz A45 AMG is the most powerful series production four-cylinder turbocharged motor (as of June 2013) and has one of the highest power density for a passenger vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">[86]</a></sup></li>
</ul>
<p>Half a century of vehicle safety innovation helped win Mercedes-Benz the Safety Award at the 2007 <i>What Car?</i> Awards.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_83-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-83">[83]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Robot_cars">Robot cars</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Robot cars">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Driverless_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Driverless car">Driverless car</a></div>
<p>In the 1980s, Mercedes built the world's first robot car, together with the team of Professor <a href="/wiki/Ernst_Dickmanns" title="Ernst Dickmanns">Ernst Dickmanns</a> at <a href="/wiki/Bundeswehr_University_Munich" title="Bundeswehr University Munich">Bundeswehr University Munich</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup> Partially encouraged by Dickmanns' success, in 1987 the European Union's <a href="/wiki/EUREKA" class="mw-redirect" title="EUREKA">EUREKA</a> programme initiated the <a href="/wiki/EUREKA_Prometheus_Project" class="mw-redirect" title="EUREKA Prometheus Project">Prometheus Project</a> on autonomous vehicles, funded to the tune of nearly 800&#160;million. A culmination point was achieved in 1995, when Dickmanns' re-engineered autonomous <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">S-Class</a> Mercedes took a long trip from <a href="/wiki/Munich" title="Munich">Munich</a> in Bavaria to <a href="/wiki/Copenhagen" title="Copenhagen">Copenhagen</a> in Denmark, and back. On highways, the robot achieved speeds exceeding 175&#160;km/h (109&#160;mph) (permissible in some areas of the German <a href="/wiki/Autobahn" title="Autobahn">Autobahn</a>).</p>
<p>In October 2015, the company introduced the Vision Tokyo, a five-seat self-driving electric van powered by a hybrid hydrogen fuel-cell system. The super-sleek van is touted as "a chill-out zone in the midst of megacity traffic mayhem." <sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">[88]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Tuners">Tuners</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Tuners">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Several companies have become <a href="/wiki/Car_tuner" class="mw-redirect" title="Car tuner">car tuners</a> (or modifiers) of Mercedes Benz, in order to increase performance and/or luxury to a given model.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG" title="Mercedes-AMG">AMG</a> is Mercedes-Benz's in-house performance-tuning division, specialising in high-performance versions of most Mercedes-Benz cars. AMG engines are all hand-built,<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[89]</a></sup> and each completed engine receives a tag with the signature of the engineer who built it. AMG has been wholly owned by Mercedes-Benz since 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[90]</a></sup> The 2009 <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_SLS_AMG" title="Mercedes-Benz SLS AMG">SLS AMG</a>, a revival of the 300SL Gullwing, is the first car to be entirely developed by AMG.</p>
<p>There are numerous independent tuners including <a href="/wiki/Brabus" title="Brabus">Brabus</a>, <a href="/wiki/Carlsson_(car_company)" title="Carlsson (car company)">Carlsson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kleemann" title="Kleemann">Kleemann</a> and <a href="/wiki/Renntech" title="Renntech">Renntech</a>.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sponsorships">Sponsorships</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mercedes-Benz&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Sponsorships">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mario_G%C3%B6tze,_Germany_national_football_team_(02).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg/150px-Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg" width="150" height="225" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg/225px-Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg/300px-Mario_G%C3%B6tze%2C_Germany_national_football_team_%2802%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="1800" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mario_G%C3%B6tze,_Germany_national_football_team_(02).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Mercedes-Benz is sponsoring the German national football team.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a>, Mercedes-Benz sponsors <a href="/wiki/Germany_National_Football_Team" class="mw-redirect" title="Germany National Football Team">Germany National Football Team</a>. Mercedes-Benz sponsors <a href="/wiki/Fu%C3%9Fball-Bundesliga" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuball-Bundesliga">Bundesliga</a> club <a href="/wiki/VfB_Stuttgart" title="VfB Stuttgart">VfB Stuttgart</a> and provides the naming rights for their stadium, the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_Arena_(Stuttgart)" title="Mercedes-Benz Arena (Stuttgart)">Mercedes-Benz Arena</a>. The company also holds the naming rights to the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_Superdome" title="Mercedes-Benz Superdome">Mercedes-Benz Superdome</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_Orleans" title="New Orleans">New Orleans</a>, <a href="/wiki/Louisiana" title="Louisiana">Louisiana</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup> On 24 August 2015, Mercedes-Benz was announced as the naming rights sponsor for the <a href="/wiki/Atlanta_Falcons" title="Atlanta Falcons">Atlanta Falcons</a>' new home <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_Stadium" title="Mercedes-Benz Stadium">Mercedes-Benz Stadium</a>, (Mercedes-Benz moved their US headquarters to the Atlanta area) scheduled to open in 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-MB_Stadium_Atlanta_92-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MB_Stadium_Atlanta-92">[92]</a></sup></p>
